<dl id="n58069f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n58" href="#n58069f">N58 (VI.B.30)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n58all.htm#n58069f"> 69(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Heavystost&apos;s / envil catacalamitumb/ling <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n58069f"><li>FW 514.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n58069f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n58069f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n58069f">MS BL 47487-213v</ms> </li><li>JJA 62:396 <a name="rAd11y" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rAd11y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd11.htm#n58069f">Draft: III&sect;3A.11</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>Hesiod</mark>, the contemporary of Homer, believed that the earth was supported like a disc midway between the vault of the sky and the infernal regions, a distance measured once, he claimed, by Vulcan&apos;s <mark>anvil</mark>, which took nine days and nine nights to <mark>fall from the sky</mark> to the earth, and the same time to fall from the earth to Tartarus. These ideas ruled for a very long time men&apos;s conceptions of the construction of the universe. <small> Camille Flammarion, <a name="CFPA" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CFPA"><cite title="source">Popular Astronomy</cite></a> (1907) 6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See units <a name="n58068c" href="n58all.htm#n58068c">N58 (VI.B.30):068(c)</a> and <a name="n58068d" href="n58all.htm#n58068d">N58 (VI.B.30):068(d)</a> above [Hesiod].</mm> </dd></dl>
